<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>

<example xml:id="sample-MX3">
    <title>MX3</title>
    <introduction>
        <p> Consider the system of equations <me>\begin{matrix} x_{1} &amp; - &amp; x_{2} &amp; -
            &amp; 3 \, x_{3} &amp; = &amp; -2 \\ 3 \, x_{1} &amp; - &amp; 2 \, x_{2} &amp; - &amp; 5
            \, x_{3} &amp; = &amp; -10 \\ x_{1} &amp; - &amp; x_{2} &amp; - &amp; 2 \, x_{3} &amp; =
            &amp; -4 \\ \end{matrix}</me> with a unique solution. </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p> Explain and demonstrate how this problem can be restated using matrix
                multiplication. </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                This is equivalent to the vector equation
                <m>T(\vec x)=\left[\begin{array}{c} -2 \\ -10 \\ -4 \end{array}\right]</m>
                where <m>T</m> has the standard matrix
                <m>\left[\begin{array}{ccc} 1 &amp; -1 &amp; -3 \\ 3 &amp; -2 &amp; -5 \\ 1 &amp;
                    -1 &amp; -2 \end{array}\right]</m>, so we may rewrite this as
                <me>\left[\begin{array}{ccc} 1 &amp; -1 &amp; -3 \\ 3 &amp; -2 &amp; -5 \\ 1 &amp;
                    -1 &amp; -2 \end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c} x_{1} \\ x_{2} \\ x_{3}
                    \end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c} -2 \\ -10 \\ -4 \end{array}\right]</me>
            </p>
        </answer>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p> Use the properties of matrix multiplication to find the unique solution. </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                Using technology to find <m>\left[\begin{array}{ccc} 1 &amp; -1 &amp; -3 \\ 3 &amp; -2 &amp; -5 \\ 1 &amp;
                    -1 &amp; -2 \end{array}\right]^{-1}=
                    \left[\begin{array}{ccc} -1 &amp; 1 &amp; -1 \\ 1 &amp; 1 &amp; -4 \\ -1 &amp; 0
                    &amp; 1 \end{array}\right]</m>,
                we have
                <me>\left[\begin{array}{ccc} -1 &amp; 1 &amp; -1 \\ 1 &amp; 1 &amp; -4 \\ -1 &amp; 0
                    &amp; 1 \end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{ccc} 1 &amp; -1 &amp; -3 \\ 3 &amp; -2 &amp; -5 \\ 1 &amp;
                    -1 &amp; -2 \end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c} x_{1} \\ x_{2} \\ x_{3}
                    \end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{ccc} -1 &amp; 1 &amp; -1 \\ 1 &amp; 1 &amp; -4 \\ -1 &amp; 0
                    &amp; 1 \end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c} -2 \\ -10 \\ -4 \end{array}\right]</me>
                and therefore see that (using technology to multiply matrices)
                <me>\left[\begin{array}{c} x_{1} \\ x_{2} \\ x_{3}
                    \end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c} -4 \\ 4 \\ -2 \end{array}\right]</me>.
            </p>
        </answer>
    </task>
</example>